          <h2 class="details-title">Lonavala and Khandala : Twin Hill Stations of Tranquility</h2>
          <p>
            Nestled in the Sahyadri range, Lonavala and Khandala are twin hill stations in the Pune district of
            Maharashtra. Known for their lush greenery, cascading waterfalls, serene lakes, and misty weather, these
            destinations are the perfect escape for nature lovers, adventure enthusiasts, and weekend travelers.
            Conveniently located close to Mumbai and Pune, they are popular for short getaways.
          </p>
          <h5>A Natural Retreat</h5>
          <p>The name Lonavala is derived from "Lonavli," meaning a group of caves, which reflects the presence of
            ancient rock-cut caves in the area. Khandala, slightly smaller but equally enchanting, is located just a few
            kilometers from Lonavala and complements its charm with its own scenic beauty.</p>
          <h5>Top Attractions in Lonavala and Khandala</h5>
          <ol>
            <li><strong>Amrutanjan Point</strong>:
              <p>Located at the beginning of Khandala Ghat, this point offers breathtaking views of the Duke’s Nose peak and the surrounding valleys.</p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://www.holidify.com/images/cmsuploads/compressed/AmrutanjanPoint1_20191213121643_20191213121711.jpg">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Sunset Point (Khandala)</strong>:
              <p>As the name suggests, this point is famous for its captivating sunsets. The golden hues of the setting sun against the backdrop of the Sahyadri hills create a mesmerizing experience.

              </p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://static.toiimg.com/thumb/msid-47340300,width=1200,height=900/47340300.jpg">
               </li>
            <li><strong>Tiger’s Leap</strong>:
              <p>Also known as Waghdari, this viewpoint resembles a tiger leaping into the valley. The breathtaking
                views of the valley below and the surrounding hills make it a must-visit spot.</p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://eindiatourism.in/wp-content/uploads/2023/05/Tiger-Leap.jpg">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Bhushi Dam</strong>:
              <p>A popular picnic spot, Bhushi Dam is known for its gushing water during the monsoon. Sitting on the
                steps of the dam as water flows over is a favorite activity for visitors.</p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://www.tourmyindia.com/states/maharashtra/images/bhushi-dam1.jpg">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Karla and Bhaja Caves</strong>:
              <p>These ancient Buddhist rock-cut caves date back to the 2nd century BC. They showcase stunning carvings,
                prayer halls (chaityas), and monasteries (viharas), offering a glimpse into history and architecture.
              </p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://dynamic-media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-o/16/70/52/da/bhaja-caves.jpg?w=900&h=500&s=1">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Lohagad Fort</strong>:
              <p>A UNESCO World Heritage Site, Lohagad Fort is a historic structure perched atop a hill. The trek to the fort is moderately easy and offers panoramic views of the region, especially during the monsoon.</p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://dynamic-media-cdn.tripadvisor.com/media/photo-o/0c/d3/55/5a/pathway-to-fort.jpg?w=900&h=500&s=1">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Rajmachi Point</strong>:
              <p>Situated in Khandala, Rajmachi Point offers stunning views of the Rajmachi Fort and the surrounding valley. It is a popular spot for photography and relaxation.</p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://www.trawell.in/admin/images/upload/080966964Lonavala_Rajmachi_Fort_Main.jpg">
            </li>
            <li><strong>Pawna Lake</strong>:
              <p>This tranquil lake surrounded by hills is ideal for camping, boating, and picnics. Its serene ambiance makes it a favorite among nature enthusiasts.
              </p>
              <br>
              <img style="max-width: 100%;max-height: 400px;"
                src="https://www.bookmyadventures.co.in/blogs/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/Pawna-lake-complete-information.jpg">
            </li>
          </ol>
          <h5>Activities to Enjoy</h5>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Trekking</strong>: Explore trails to forts like Lohagad, Visapur, and Rajmachi.</li>
            <li><strong>Camping</strong>: Spend a night under the stars by Pawna Lake.</li>
            <li><strong>Waterfalls</strong>: Visit waterfalls like Kune Falls and reverse waterfalls near Lonavala during the monsoon.</li>
            <li><strong>Shopping</strong>: Don’t miss buying chikki (a sweet made of jaggery and nuts) and fudge, which are local specialties.</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Best Time to Visit</h5>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Monsoon (June to September)</strong>: The hills turn lush green, and waterfalls are in full flow, making it the best time for nature enthusiasts.</li>
            <li><strong>Winter (October to February)</strong>: The cool and pleasant weather is perfect for trekking and sightseeing.</li>
            <li><strong>Summer (March to May)</strong>: Although slightly warmer, the mornings and evenings remain pleasant.</li>
          </ul>
          <h5>Tips for Travelers</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Carry rain gear if visiting during the monsoon as heavy showers are common.</li>
            <li>Wear comfortable footwear for trekking and exploring caves.</li>
            <li>Start early to avoid crowds, especially at popular viewpoints and dams.</li>
          </ul>
